<section xml:id="section-cartesian-graphs">

    <title>Cartesian Graphs</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>When we model real-life data with graphs, we use the <term>Cartesian coordinate system</term>. In this section, we will learn the basics of Cartesian coordinate system. We will start with a video lecture as an overview.</p>

        <figure><video youtube="N4nrdf0yYfM" /></figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Cartesian Coordinate System</title>

        <p>The Cartesian coordinate system is just a way to identify <em>where</em> points are on a flat area. It's basically an address, so we will start with an example that uses a street grid. Here is a street map with Carl's home at the center, covering some nearby businesses. Assume each unit represents <m>1</m> mile.</p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-carls-neighborhood">
            <caption>Carl's neighborhood</caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <description>a Cartesian grid with Carl's home at (0,0), a restaurant at (2, 3), a pet shop at (-3,2), a gas station at (-2,-4), and a bar at (3, -3)</description>
                <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[xlabel={},ylabel={},
                                xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                xtick={-4,4},
                                ytick={-4,4},
                                clip=false]
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[pin=240:{Carl's house}] {};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2, 3)} node[pin=-30:{restaurant}] {};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 2)} node[pin=100:{pet shop}] {};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, -4)} node[pin=150:{gas station}] {};
                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, -3)} node[pin=120:{bar}] {};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(5, 0)} node[above left] {east};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-5, 0)} node[above right] {west};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[below right] {north};
                        \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, -5)} node[above right] {south};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>If Carl has an out of town guest who asks him how to get to the restaurant, one way to give directions is:</p>
        <blockquote><p><q>Go <m>2</m> miles to the east, and then <m>3</m> miles to the north.</q></p></blockquote>

        <sidebyside>
            <p>We can see that two numbers are needed to locate the restaurant. In a Cartesian coordinate system, we write these numbers this way: <m>(2,3)</m>, to represent the restaurant's location. Note that the first number, <m>2</m>, represents the location in the east-west direction, and the second number, <m>3</m>, represents the location in north-south direction.</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Carl's neighborhood</caption>
                <image>
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with Carl's home at (0,0), a restaurant at (2, 3), a pet shop at (-3,2), a gas station at (-2,-4), and a bar at (3, -3)</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xlabel={},ylabel={},
                                    xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                    ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    xtick={-4,4},
                                    ytick={-4,4},
                                    clip=false]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[pin=240:{Carl's house}] {};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2, 3)} node[pin=-30:{restaurant}] {} node[left] {$(2,3)$};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(5, 0)} node[above left] {east};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-5, 0)} node[above right] {west};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[below right] {north};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, -5)} node[above right] {south};
                            \addplot[primarycurve,-] coordinates {(0,0) (2,0)} node[below,pos=0.5] {right $2$};
                            \addplot[primarycurve,->] coordinates {(2,0) (2,2.8)} node[below,pos=0.5,rotate=90] {up $3$};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>To travel from Carl's home to the pet shop, he would go <m>3</m> miles west, and then <m>2</m> miles north.</p>

        <sidebyside>
            <p>We think of rightward and upward as <em>positive</em> directions, and leftward and downward as <em>negative</em> directions. So we use positive numbers to represent the east, and negative numbers to represent the west. The pet shop's location would be <m>(-3,2)</m> in a Cartesian coordinate system.</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Carl's neighborhood</caption>
                <image>
                    <description>a Cartesian grid with Carl's home at (0,0), a restaurant at (2, 3), a pet shop at (-3,2), a gas station at (-2,-4), and a bar at (3, -3)</description>
                    <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xlabel={},ylabel={},
                                    xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                    ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    xtick={-4,4},
                                    ytick={-4,4},
                                    clip=false]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[pin=240:{Carl's house}] {};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 2)} node[pin=100:{pet shop}] {} node[above right] {$(-3,2)$};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(5, 0)} node[above left] {east};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-5, 0)} node[above right] {west};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, 5)} node[below right] {north};
                            \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(0, -5)} node[above right] {south};
                            \addplot[primarycurve,-] coordinates {(0,0) (-3,0)} node[below,pos=0.5] {left $3$};
                            \addplot[primarycurve,->] coordinates {(-3,0) (-3,1.8)} node[below,pos=0.5,rotate=90] {up $2$};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

        </sidebyside>

