        <p>In a Cartesian coordinate system, the map would look like this:</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Carl's Neighborhood in a Cartesian Coordinate System</caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <description>a Cartesian grid points <m>(0,0), (2, 3), (-3,2), (-2,-4),</m> and <m>(3, -3)</m>, with <m>x</m>-axis and <m>y</m>-axis labeled</description>
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                    ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    xtick={-4,4},
                                    ytick={-4,4}]
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[above right] {(0,0)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2, 3)} node[above] {(2,3)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 2)} node[above] {(-3,2)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, -4)} node[above] {(-2,-4)};
                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, -3)} node[above] {(3,-3)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>It's traditional to use the variable <m>x</m> to represent numbers on the east-west axis, so we call that axis the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>. For similar reasons we call the north-south axis the <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>. The point <m>(0,0)</m> is where the two axes meet, and we call it the <term>origin</term>. <index><main>origin</main></index> We use an <term>ordered pair</term>, like <m>(2,3)</m>, to represent the location of a point.</p>

        <p>Note that the first number in an ordered pair always represents an <m>x</m>-value, and the second number represents a <m>y</m>-value, and together they give an address for a point. It's like we always say the east-west distance first, and then north-south. This is the Cartesian coordinate system's convention. The following is a formal definition.</p>

        <aside><p>Unfortunately, the way we write ordered pairs looks exactly like the way we write open intervals in interval notation. It's up to you to use <em>context</em> to understand if something like <m>(2,3)</m> is the point <m>2</m> units right of the origin and <m>3</m> units up, or the interval of all numbers between <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.</p></aside>

        <definition>
            <title>Cartesian Coordinate System</title>
            <index><main>Cartesian</main><sub>Coordinate System</sub></index>
            <statement>
                <p>A Cartesian coordinate system is a coordinate system that specifies each point uniquely in a plane by a pair of numerical coordinates, which are the signed distances to the point from two fixed perpendicular directed lines, measured in the same unit of length. Those two reference lines are called the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term> and <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>, and the point where they meet is its <term>origin</term>, usually at the <term>ordered pair</term> <m>(0, 0)</m>. (Visit <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinate_system">Wikipedia</url> for more.)</p>

                <p>The plane based on the <m>x</m>-axis and <m>y</m>-axis is called a <term>coordinate plane</term>. The ordered pair used to locate a point is called the point's <term>coordinates</term>, which consists of an <term><m>x</m>-coordinate</term> and a <term><m>y</m>-coordinate</term>. For example, for the point <m>(1,2)\text{,}</m> its <m>x</m>-coordinate is <m>1\text{,}</m> and its <m>y</m>-coordinate is <m>2\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>A Cartesian coordinate system is divided into four <term>quardrants</term>, as shown in <xref ref="figure-quadrants">Figure</xref>.</p>

                <figure xml:id="figure-quadrants">
                    <caption>A Cartesian grid with four quardrants marked</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description>a Cartesian grid with Quardrant I marked in the top right section, Quardrant II marked in the top left section, Quardrant III marked in the bottom left section, Quardrant IV marked in the bottom right section.</description>
                        <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=5,
                                        ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                        xtick={-4,-3,...,4},
                                        ytick={-4,-3,...,4}]
                                \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(3,3)} node[below] {Quardrant I};
                                \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-3, 3)} node[below] {Quardrant II};
                                \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(-3, -3)} node[above] {Quardrant III};
                                \addplot[mark=none] coordinates {(3, -3)} node[above] {Quardrant IV};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
        </definition>


