    <subsection>
        <title>Decide whether a Point is on a Line</title>

        <p>We just learned how to build a table of values based on a given equation. A related skill is to decide whether a given point is on a given line. We will look at an example.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Decide whether the points <m>(5,-2)</m> and <m>(-10,-7)</m> on the line <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>If the point <m>(5,-2)</m> is on <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{,}</m> once we substitute <m>x=5</m> and <m>y=-2</m> into the line's equaiton, the equation should be true. We will try both points:<md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{3}{5}x+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-\frac{3}{5}(5)+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=} -3+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=} -2</mrow>
                </md>Because <m>-2=-2</m> is true, we can determine that the point <m>(5,-2)</m> is on the line <m>y=-\frac{3}{5}x+1\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>If we substitute <m>x=-10</m> and <m>y=-7</m> into the equation, we will get <m>-7 \ne 7</m>, implying the point <m>(-10,-7)</m> is not on the line.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

